    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3848650472" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3848650472" />
    <a title="Elizabeth A.G." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67736000-elizabeth-a-g"><img alt="Elizabeth A.G." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1521007896p2/67736000.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3848650472?book_show_action=true">Feb 22, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth A.G." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth A.G." href="/user/show/67736000-elizabeth-a-g">Elizabeth A.G.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/55046992-dust-tracks-on-a-road">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3848650472" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16417668273064572480">Not your usual autobiography, but what do you expect from this unusual woman? Her curiosity and indomitable spirit, even as a child, served her well in spite of the ups and downs of her life. The folksy style of writing and the stories she inserts into the telling of her own story are funny and fanciful and reflect the imagination that is inherent in story-telling. The reader has to question what is real or exaggerated. After the death of her mother and remarriage of her father, Zora&apos;s incompati</span>
  <span id="freeText16417668273064572480" style="display:none">Not your usual autobiography, but what do you expect from this unusual woman? Her curiosity and indomitable spirit, even as a child, served her well in spite of the ups and downs of her life. The folksy style of writing and the stories she inserts into the telling of her own story are funny and fanciful and reflect the imagination that is inherent in story-telling. The reader has to question what is real or exaggerated. After the death of her mother and remarriage of her father, Zora's incompatibility (to say the least) with her step-mother leads to her leaving the family home. She works as a maid, waitress, and manicurist. With her determinism and help from others who recognized her talents, she manages to complete high school and go on to Howard University, graduated Barnard, and studied at Columbia with training in anthropology. The last few chapters in the book seem to be more like essays presenting Hurston's thoughts and arguments regarding the diversity within her own race, love, religion, universal justice, positivity, and useless resentment and blaming regarding the past. She resolves to focus on the present and future: "I know I cannot pry aloose the clutching hand of Time, so I will turn all my thoughts and energies on the present. I will settle for from now on." And, "While I have a handkerchief over my eyes crying over the landing of the first slaves in 1619, I might miss something swell that is going on in 1942." But even in these "essays" she inserts her humor. <br /> <br />Hurston was criticized in her day for avoiding mention of racial inequities and for not supporting racial justice in her autobiography. She was thought to be pandering in not condemning supposed white superiority and treatment of Black Americans. Her other books were criticized by Black critics for her adamant exclusion of the Southern Negro experiences of exploitation, misery, and racial violence. Her works were focused on Black American culture and folklore. This is a captivating look into Zora Neale Hurston's thoughts on her life. Sadly, she had been relegated to virtual obscurity until a renewed interest in her writing was instigated by author Alice Walker in the late 20th century (1975). I am now interested in reading a biography of this author - perhaps <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38069.Zora_Neale_Hurston_A_Literary_Biography" title="Zora Neale Hurston A Literary Biography by Robert E. Hemenway" rel="nofollow noopener">Zora Neale Hurston: A Literary Biography</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/21411.Robert_E__Hemenway" title="Robert E. Hemenway" rel="nofollow noopener">Robert E. Hemenway</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16417668273064572480" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


